":"Edinburgh, Skotland","Craigmillar, Midlothian, Scotland":"Craigmillar, Midlothian, Skotland","Crichton Castle, England":"Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Preston, Haddingtonshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1278–about 1337":"circa 1278–circa 1337","1278–1337":"1278–1337","1297–1361":"1297–1361","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1305–Male":"1305–Overleden","1252–1329":"1252–1329","1240–1283":"1240–1283","1297":"1297","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1361":"1361","1283":"1283","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","about 1329":"circa 1329","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","about 1337":"circa 1337","about 1278":"circa 1278","1329":"1329","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Schotland","Craigmillar, Midlothian, Scotland":"Craigmillar, Midlothian, Schotland","Crichton Castle, England":"Castle, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Preston, Haddingtonshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1278–about 1337":"about 1278–about 1337","1278–1337":"1278–1337","1297–1361":"1297–1361","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1252–1329":"1252–1329","1240–1283":"1240–1283","1297":"1297","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1361":"1361","1283":"1283","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","about 1329":"about 1329","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","about 1337":"about 1337","about 1278":"about 1278","1329":"1329","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","Craigmillar, Midlothian, Scotland":"Craigmillar, Midlothian, Scotland","Crichton Castle, England":"Castle, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Preston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from one of the many places (most notably one in Lancashire) so called from Old English <i>prēost</i> ‘priest’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","occasionally from Middle English <i>prest</i> + <i>son</i> ‘son of the priest’. Priests were forbidden marriage but many produced illegitimate offspring."],"variants":[{"name":"Presson","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): variant of   Preston  .","French: occupational name for a presser of wine or oil, from a derivative of <i>presser</i> ‘to press’."]},{"name":"Prestwich","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place in Lancashire (now Greater Manchester), so called from Old English <i>prēost</i> ‘priest’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying settlement’, or from other places with the same derivation. Variants such as <i>Prestidge</i>, <i>Prestage</i>, etc., parallel the local pronunciation of the Lancashire name. Compare   Preston  ."]}]},{"name":"Laurence","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a French form of Latin <i>Laurentius</i> ‘man from Laurentum’. <i>Laurentum</i> was a town in Latium, which may have got its name from Latin <i>laurus</i> ‘laurel’, although it is more probably of pre-Roman origin. The given name was moderately popular in the Middle Ages (when it was used for girls as well as boys), under the influence of a 3rd-century saint who was one of the seven deacons of Rome. He was martyred in  258 . The legend is that, having been required to hand over the Church's treasures to the civil authorities, he assembled the poor and sick and presented them. For this act of Christian defiance, he was roasted to death on a gridiron. In England the name is also associated with  St Laurence of Canterbury  (  d. 619 ). A more recent influence has been the actor  Sir Laurence Olivier  (  1907–89 ).  See also  Lawrence ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Laurence de Preston Knight- General was born about 1278, in Edinburgh, Scotland, his father, Nicholas de Preston, was 27 and his mother, Eda, was 39. He had at least 3 sons. He died about 1337, in Craigmillar, Midlothian, Scotland, at the age of 61."},"et":{"about 1278–about 1337":"umbes 1278–umbes 1337","1278–1337":"1278–1337","1297–1361":"1297–1361","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1252–1329":"1252–1329","1240–1283":"1240–1283","1297":"1297","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1361":"1361","1283":"1283","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","about 1329":"umbes 1329","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","about 1337":"umbes 1337","about 1278":"umbes 1278","1329":"1329","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","Craigmillar, Midlothian, Scotland":"Craigmillar, Midlothian, Scotland","Crichton Castle, England":"Castle, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Preston, Haddingtonshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1278–about 1337":"noin 1278–noin 1337","1278–1337":"1278–1337","1297–1361":"1297–1361","1300–Male":"1300–Kuollut","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1252–1329":"1252–1329","1240–1283":"1240–1283","1297":"1297","1252":"1252","1240":"1240","1361":"1361","1283":"1283","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","about 1329":"noin 1329","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","about 1337":"noin 1337","about 1278":"noin 1278","1329":"1329","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Scotland","Craigmillar, Midlothian, Scotland":"Craigmillar, Midlothian, Scotland","Crichton Castle, England":"Castle, Northumberland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Preston, Haddingtonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Preston, Haddingtonshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistyn